  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Keil and Delitzsch Biblical Commentary on the Old Testament",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "The poet now begins himself to do that to which he encourages Israel. Jahve is Israel's God: His righteous rule extends over the whole earth, whilst His people experience His inviolable faithfulness to His covenant. יהוה in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Psalm 105:7",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " is in apposition to הוּא, for the God who bears this name is as a matter of course the object of the song of praise. זכר is the perfect of practically pledges certainty (cf. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Psalm 111:5",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", where we find instead the future of confident prospect). The chronicler has זכרוּ instead (lxx again something different: μνημονεύωμεν); but the object is not the demanding but the promissory side of the covenant, so that consequently it is not Israel's remembering but God's that is spoken of. He remembers His covenant in all time to come, so that exile and want of independence as a state are only temporary, exceptional conditions. צוּה has its radical signification here, to establish, institute, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Psalm 111:9",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". לאלף דּור (in which expression דור is a specifying accusative) is taken from ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Deuteronomy 7:9",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". And since דּבר is the covenant word of promise, it can be continued אשׁר כּרת; and ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Haggai 2:5",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " (vid., Khler thereon) shows that אשׁר is not joined to בריתו over ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Psalm 105:8",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". וּשׁבוּעתו, however, is a second object to זכר (since דּבר with what belongs to it as an apposition is out of the question). It is the oath on Moriah (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Genesis 22:16",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") that is meant, which applied to Abraham and his seed. לישׂחק (chronicler ליצחק), as in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Amos 7:9",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Jeremiah 33:26",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". To זכר is appended ויּעמרדה; the suffix, intended as neuter, points to what follows, viz., this, that Canaan shall be Israel's hereditary land. From Abraham and Isaac we come to Jacob-Israel, who as being the father of the twelve is the twelve-tribe nation itself that is coming into existence; hence the plural can alternate with the singular in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Psalm 105:11",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". את־ארץ כּנען (chronicler, without the את) is an accusative of the object, and חבל נחלתכם accusative of the predicate: the land of Canaan as the province of your own hereditary possession measured out with a measuring line (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Psalm 78:55",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). ",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  }
]